<paragraph id="4B3E36DDFFB7BA44FF3DF8F7FD66ED3B" blockId="39.[151,651,1757,1817]" box="[151,651,1792,1817]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">
<emphasis id="79F5EACFFFB7BA44FF3DF8F7FEBAED3B" bold="true" box="[151,343,1792,1817]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">Common name:</emphasis>
The lesser Egyptian gerbil.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="039B6556FFB7BA4BFF3DF8BFFE5EEFF3" lastPageId="40" lastPageNumber="41" pageId="39" pageNumber="40" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="4B3E36DDFFB7BA44FF3DF8BFFD6EEDD3" blockId="39.[151,1437,1864,2033]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">
<emphasis id="79F5EACFFFB7BA44FF3DF8BFFEE7ED43" bold="true" box="[151,266,1864,1889]" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">Diagnosis</emphasis>
: Medium-sized gerbil. Ears small, sandy buff in color and pigmented. Fur color pale sandy buff dorsally, white ventrally, with distinct line of demarcation (
<figureCitation id="D3BA2A58FFB7BA44FD71F89BFCBDEDA6" box="[731,848,1900,1925]" captionStart="FIGURE 44" captionStartId="41.[151,250,941,963]" captionTargetBox="[196,1364,145,912]" captionTargetId="figure@41.[196,1364,145,912]" captionTargetPageId="41" captionText="FIGURE 44. The lesser Egyptian gerbil, Gerbillus gerbillus (photo by Mohammad Abu Baker)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1202863/files/figure.png" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">Figure 44</figureCitation>
). White patch behind ear and above eye and rump distinct. Feet with fringes of hair. Soles not pigmented. Tail covered with short hair, moderate terminal pencil present. Skull with flat and broad braincase. Posterior margin of nasals rounded. Upper incisor very narrow. First lower molar with distinct cusps (
<figureCitation id="D3BA2A58FFB7BA44FDAFF82FFD9AEDD3" box="[517,631,2008,2033]" captionStart="FIGURE 45" captionStartId="41.[151,250,2001,2023]" captionTargetBox="[290,1283,1012,1977]" captionTargetId="figure@41.[290,1283,1012,1977]" captionTargetPageId="41" captionText="FIGURE 45.A. Dorsal,B. Ventral, C. Lateral views for the skull, and D. Upper maxillary teeth for Gerbillus gerbillus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1202865/files/figure.png" pageId="39" pageNumber="40">Figure 45</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption id="1FFE6655FFB8BA4BFF3DFAA0FCDEEF4F" box="[151,819,1367,1389]" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1202861/files/figure.png" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" startId="40.[151,250,1367,1389]" targetBox="[278,1271,226,1322]" targetPageId="40">
<paragraph id="4B3E36DDFFB8BA4BFF3DFAA0FCDEEF4F" blockId="40.[151,819,1367,1389]" box="[151,819,1367,1389]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">
<emphasis id="79F5EACFFFB8BA4BFF3DFAA0FECDEF4E" bold="true" box="[151,288,1367,1389]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">FIGURE 43.</emphasis>
Distribution of Wagner's gerbil, 
<taxonomicName id="8C814D5EFFB8BA4BFDC6FAA0FCC3EF4F" baseAuthorityName="Wagner" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[620,814,1367,1389]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Gerbillus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="dasyurus">
<emphasis id="79F5EACFFFB8BA4BFDC6FAA0FCC3EF4F" box="[620,814,1367,1389]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Gerbillus dasyurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="4B3E36DDFFB8BA4BFF6DFA63FE5EEFF3" blockId="40.[151,1437,1428,2030]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">
<emphasis id="79F5EACFFFB8BA4BFF6DFA63FDF4EF8F" bold="true" box="[199,537,1428,1453]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Localities: Previous records.</emphasis>
‘Aqaba (
<bibRefCitation id="2F104B2CFFB8BA4BFD2BFA63FCE7EF8F" box="[641,778,1428,1453]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" refId="ref30777" refString="Allen, G. M. (1915) Mammals obtained by the Phillips Palestine Expedition. Bulletin of the Museum of Comparative Zoolology of Harvard University, 59 (1), 3 - 14." type="journal article">Allen, 1915</bibRefCitation>
); Quraiqira, Ar Rīshah, Gharandal, Raḩmah (
<bibRefCitation id="2F104B2CFFB8BA4BFAAEFA63FEF2EFF3" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" refId="ref30224" refString="Abu Baker, M. &amp; Amr, Z. (2003 b) Rodent diversity in the Northeastern Desert of Jordan, with special reference on the ecology of Gerbillus cheesmani. (Mammalia: Rodentia). Casopis Narodniho Muzea, Rada prirodovedna, 172 (1 - 4), 141 - 152." type="journal article">Abu Baker &amp; Amr, 2003b</bibRefCitation>
) (
<figureCitation id="D3BA2A58FFB8BA4BFE9FFA4FFE4AEFF3" box="[309,423,1464,1489]" captionStart="FIGURE 46" captionStartId="42.[151,250,1423,1445]" captionTargetBox="[275,1307,228,1368]" captionTargetId="figure@42.[264,1323,193,1401]" captionTargetPageId="42" captionText="FIGURE 46. Distribution of the lesser Egyptian gerbil, Gerbillus gerbillus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1202867/files/figure.png" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Figure 46</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="039B6556FFB8BA4BFF6DFA2BFEC0ED34" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" type="description">
<paragraph id="4B3E36DDFFB8BA4BFF6DFA2BFEC0ED34" blockId="40.[151,1437,1428,2030]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">
<emphasis id="79F5EACFFFB8BA4BFF6DFA2BFEC1EFD7" bold="true" box="[199,300,1500,1525]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Habitat:</emphasis>
It strictly inhabits areas and patches of soft, wind-blown sand dunes dominated with 
<taxonomicName id="8C814D5EFFB8BA4BFA8DFA2BFDB8EC3B" authority="(Abu Baker &amp; Amr, 2003 a)" authorityName="Abu Baker &amp; Amr" authorityYear="2003" baseAuthorityName="Abu Baker &amp; Amr" baseAuthorityYear="2003" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Amaranthaceae" genus="Haloxylon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="persicum">
<emphasis id="79F5EACFFFB8BA4BFA8DFA2BFF13EC3B" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Haloxylon persicum</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="2F104B2CFFB8BA4BFEBBF9F7FDA0EC3B" box="[273,589,1536,1561]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" refId="ref30180" refString="Abu Baker, M. &amp; Amr, Z. (2003 a) A morphometric and taxonomic revision of the genus Gerbillus in Jordan with notes on its current distribution. Zoologische Abhandlungen (Dresden), 53, 177 - 204." type="journal article">Abu Baker &amp; Amr, 2003a</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. This species was reported from dunes and alluvium in wadis in Sinai Peninsula (Haim &amp; Tchernov, 1974) and sandy patches in palm groves and cultivated areas in the Nile Valley and Delta in Egypt (Osborn &amp; Helmy, 1980). It was found in association with the naked-footed gerbil, 
<taxonomicName id="8C814D5EFFB8BA4BFB4CF9BEFAAAEC43" baseAuthorityName="Thomas" baseAuthorityYear="1918" box="[1254,1351,1609,1633]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Gerbillus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="nanus">
<emphasis id="79F5EACFFFB8BA4BFB4CF9BEFAAAEC43" box="[1254,1351,1609,1633]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">G. nanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
around lower wadis and salt marshes with 
<taxonomicName id="8C814D5EFFB8BA4BFD9BF999FCC9ECA4" authority="in Ra" authorityName="in Hazim. Furthermore, Abu Dieyeh" authorityYear="1988" box="[561,804,1645,1670]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Nitrariaceae" genus="Nitraria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="retusa">
<emphasis id="79F5EACFFFB8BA4BFD9BF999FD36ECA7" box="[561,731,1646,1669]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Nitraria retusa</emphasis>
in Ra
</taxonomicName>
ḩmah area. Sinai 
<emphasis id="79F5EACFFFB8BA4BFC5AF999FBC9ECA4" box="[1008,1060,1645,1670]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">et al</emphasis>
. (2003) studied the ecology and behaviour of this gerbil in &quot;sand islands&quot; and in the mainland. They found that the home range in the mainland for males was significantly larger than that for females, but the other way around in &quot;sand islands&quot;. No obvious sexual dimorphism in body mass was observed among the &quot;island&quot; population; however, &quot;mainland&quot; males were heavier than females.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="039B6556FFB8BA4BFF6DF8D7FB0CEDA3" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="4B3E36DDFFB8BA4BFF6DF8D7FB0CEDA3" blockId="40.[151,1437,1428,2030]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">
<emphasis id="79F5EACFFFB8BA4BFF6DF8D7FEC7ED1B" bold="true" box="[199,298,1824,1849]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Biology:</emphasis>
The lesser Egyptian gerbil is a nocturnal species. Burrows are usually 30 to 60 centimetres in depth. This gerbil is a social animal, living in groups sharing the same burrow. Breeding season is between January and May. Gestation period lasts for 22 days, with the average litter containing between 3 and 6 young.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="039B6556FFB8BA4BFF6DF87BFBC3EDCF" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="4B3E36DDFFB8BA4BFF6DF87BFBC3EDCF" blockId="40.[151,1437,1428,2030]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">
<emphasis id="79F5EACFFFB8BA4BFF6DF87BFED9ED87" bold="true" box="[199,308,1932,1957]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">Remarks</emphasis>
: 
<taxonomicName id="8C814D5EFFB8BA4BFEEEF879FE24ED87" authorityName="gerbillus (Olivier" authorityYear="1801" box="[324,457,1932,1957]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Gerbillus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="gerbillus">
<emphasis id="79F5EACFFFB8BA4BFEEEF879FE24ED87" box="[324,457,1932,1957]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">G. gerbillus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have a 2N= 
<quantity id="8C799B38FFB8BA4BFDFCF87AFD7EED87" box="[598,659,1932,1957]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0668" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" unit="in" value="42.0">42 in</quantity>
females/ 
<quantity id="8C799B38FFB8BA4BFD56F87BFCD8ED87" box="[764,821,1932,1957]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0922" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" unit="in" value="43.0">43 in</quantity>
males and FN=70 (female specimen). The autosomal complement of the female includes 18 metacentric, 10 submetacentric, 6 acrocentric and 6 telocentric chromosomes. The X is a large acrocentric chromosome (
<bibRefCitation id="2F104B2CFFB8BA4BFCB6F822FBCFEDCF" box="[796,1058,2005,2030]" pageId="40" pageNumber="41" refId="ref30364" refString="Abu Baker, M., Khalil, A., Sheyab, F. &amp; Amr, Z. (2009) A karyotypic study on rodents of the genus Gerbillus collected from Jordan. Vertebrate Zoology, 59 (1), 111 - 116." type="journal article">
Abu Baker 
<emphasis id="79F5EACFFFB8BA4BFC35F821FC3DEDCC" box="[927,976,2005,2030]" italics="true" pageId="40" pageNumber="41">et al</emphasis>
., 2009
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
